# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: analog-circuit-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Examples of *analog signal processing* include crossover filters in loudspeakers, "bass", "treble" and "volume" controls on stereos, and "tint" controls on television sets.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Common analog processing elements include capacitors, resistors and inductors (as the passive elements) and transistors or op-amps (as the active elements).
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Input signals are usually called *x*(*t*) or *X*(*s*) and output signals are usually called *y*(*t*) or *Y*(*s*).
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Convolution is the basic concept in signal processing that states an input signal can be combined with the system's function to find the output signal.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] It is the integral of the product of two waveforms after one has reversed and shifted; the symbol for convolution is *.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] That is the convolution integral and is used to find the convolution of a signal and a system; typically *a* = −∞ and *b* = +∞.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] By calculating the convolution, we determine how much a reversed function *g* must be shifted along the x-axis to become identical to function *f*.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The convolution function essentially reverses and slides function *g* along the axis, and calculates the integral of their (*f* and the reversed and shifted *g*) product for each possible amount of sliding.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] When the functions match, the value of (*f* * *g*) is maximized.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] This occurs because when positive areas (peaks) or negative areas (troughs) are multiplied, they contribute to the integral.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The Fourier transform is a function that transforms a signal or system in the time domain into the frequency domain, but it only works for certain functions.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Usually the Fourier transform integral is not used to determine the transform; instead, a table of transform pairs is used to find the Fourier transform of a signal or system.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Each signal or system that can be transformed has a unique Fourier transform.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] There is only one time signal for any frequency signal, and vice versa.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The Laplace transform is a generalized Fourier transform.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] It allows a transform of any system or signal because it is a transform into the complex plane instead of just the jω line like the Fourier transform.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The major difference is that the Laplace transform has a region of convergence for which the transform is valid.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] This implies that a signal in frequency may have more than one signal in time; the correct time signal for the transform is determined by the region of convergence.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] If the region of convergence includes the *jω* axis, *jω* can be substituted into the Laplace transform for *s* and it is the same as the Fourier transform.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Bode plots are plots of magnitude vs. frequency and phase vs. frequency for a system.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The phase axis is in either degrees or radians.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The frequency axes are in a [logarithmic scale].
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] These are useful because for sinusoidal inputs, the output is the input multiplied by the value of the magnitude plot at the frequency and shifted by the value of the phase plot at the frequency.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] This is the domain that most people are familiar with.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] A plot in the time domain shows the amplitude of the signal with respect to time.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] A plot in the frequency domain shows either the phase shift or magnitude of a signal at each frequency that it exists at.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] These can be found by taking the Fourier transform of a time signal and are plotted similarly to a bode plot.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] While any signal can be used in analog signal processing, there are many types of signals that are used very frequently.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Sinusoids are the building block of analog signal processing.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] All real world signals can be represented as an infinite sum of sinusoidal functions via a Fourier series.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] A sinusoidal function can be represented in terms of an exponential by the application of Euler's formula.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] An impulse (Dirac delta function) is defined as a signal that has an infinite magnitude and an infinitesimally narrow width with an area under it of one, centered at zero.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] An impulse can be represented as an infinite sum of sinusoids that includes all possible frequencies.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] It is not, in reality, possible to generate such a signal, but it can be sufficiently approximated with a large amplitude, narrow pulse, to produce the theoretical impulse response in a network to a high degree of accuracy.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] If an impulse is used as an input to a system, the output is known as the impulse response.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] A unit step function, also called the Heaviside step function, is a signal that has a magnitude of zero before zero and a magnitude of one after zero.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] If a step is used as the input to a system, the output is called the step response.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The step response shows how a system responds to a sudden input, similar to turning on a switch.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The period before the output stabilizes is called the transient part of a signal.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] The step response can be multiplied with other signals to show how the system responds when an input is suddenly turned on.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Linearity means that if you have two inputs and two corresponding outputs, if you take a linear combination of those two inputs you will get a linear combination of the outputs.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] An example of a linear system is a first order low-pass or high-pass filter.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Linear systems are made out of analog devices that demonstrate linear properties.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] These devices do not have to be entirely linear, but must have a region of operation that is linear.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] An operational amplifier is a non-linear device, but has a region of operation that is linear, so it can be modeled as linear within that region of operation.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Time-invariance means it doesn't matter when you start a system, the same output will result.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] For example, if you have a system and put an input into it today, you would get the same output if you started the system tomorrow instead.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] There are not any real systems that are LTI, but many systems can be modeled as LTI for simplicity in determining what their output will be.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] All systems have some dependence on things like temperature, signal level or other factors that cause them to be non-linear or non-time-invariant, but most are stable enough to model as LTI.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Linearity and time-invariance are important because they are the only types of systems that can be easily solved using conventional analog signal processing methods.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analog-signal-processing] Once a system becomes non-linear or non-time-invariant, it becomes a non-linear differential equations problem, and there are very few of those that can actually be solved.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] An analogue signal uses some attribute of the medium to convey the signal's information.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] For example, an aneroid barometer uses the angular position of a needle on top of a contracting and expanding box as the signal to convey the information of changes in atmospheric pressure.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Electrical signals may represent information by changing their voltage, current, frequency, or total charge.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Information is converted from some other physical form (such as sound, light, temperature, pressure, position) to an electrical signal by a transducer which converts one type of energy into another (e.g. a microphone).
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] The signals take any value from a given range, and each unique signal value represents different information.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Any change in the signal is meaningful, and each level of the signal represents a different level of the phenomenon that it represents.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] For example, suppose the signal is being used to represent temperature, with one volt representing one degree Celsius.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] In such a system, 10 volts would represent 10 degrees, and 10.1 volts would represent 10.1 degrees.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Another method of conveying an analogue signal is to use modulation.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] In this, some base carrier signal has one of its properties altered: amplitude modulation (AM) involves altering the amplitude of a sinusoidal voltage waveform by the source information, frequency modulation (FM) changes the frequency.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Other techniques, such as phase modulation or changing the phase of the carrier signal, are also used.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] In an analogue sound recording, the variation in pressure of a sound striking a microphone creates a corresponding variation in the current passing through it or voltage across it.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] An increase in the volume of the sound causes the fluctuation of the current or voltage to increase proportionally while keeping the same waveform or shape.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Mechanical, pneumatic, hydraulic, and other systems may also use analogue signals.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Analogue systems invariably include noise, random disturbances or variations, some caused by the random thermal vibrations of atomic particles.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Since all variations of an analogue signal are significant, any disturbance is equivalent to a change in the original signal and so appears as noise.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] As the signal is copied and re-copied, or transmitted over long distances, these random variations become more significant and lead to signal degradation.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Other sources of noise may include crosstalk from other signals or poorly designed components.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] These disturbances may be reduced by use of shielding and low-noise amplifiers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Since the information is encoded differently in analogue and digital electronics, the way they process a signal is consequently different.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] All operations that can be performed on an analogue signal such as amplification, filtering, limiting, and others, can also be duplicated in the digital domain.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Every digital circuit is also an analogue circuit, in that the behaviour of any digital circuit can be explained using the rules of analogue circuits.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] The use of microelectronics has made digital devices cheap and widely available.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] The effect of noise on an analogue circuit is a function of the level of noise.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] The greater the noise level, the more the analogue signal is disturbed, slowly becoming less usable.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Because of this, analogue signals are said to "fail gracefully".
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Analogue signals can still contain intelligible information with very high levels of noise.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Digital circuits, on the other hand, are not affected at all by the presence of noise until a certain threshold is reached, at which point they fail catastrophically.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] For digital telecommunications, it is possible to increase the noise threshold with the use of error detection and correction coding schemes and algorithms.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Nevertheless, there is still a point at which catastrophic failure of the link occurs.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] In digital electronics, because the information is quantized, as long as the signal stays inside a range of values, it represents the same information.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] In digital circuits the signal is regenerated at each logic gate, lessening or removing noise.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] In analogue circuits, signal loss can be regenerated with amplifiers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] However, noise is cumulative throughout the system and the amplifier itself will add to the noise according to its noise figure.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] A number of factors affect how precise a signal is, mainly the noise present in the original signal and the noise added by processing (see signal-to-noise ratio).
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Fundamental physical limits such as the shot noise in components limits the resolution of analogue signals.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] In digital electronics additional precision is obtained by using additional digits to represent the signal.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] The practical limit in the number of digits is determined by the performance of the analogue-to-digital converter (ADC), since digital operations can usually be performed without loss of precision.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] The ADC takes an analogue signal and changes it into a series of binary numbers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] The ADC may be used in simple digital display devices, e. g., thermometers or light meters but it may also be used in digital sound recording and in data acquisition.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] However, a digital-to-analogue converter (DAC) is used to change a digital signal to an analogue signal.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] A DAC takes a series of binary numbers and converts it to an analogue signal.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] It is common to find a DAC in the gain-control system of an op-amp which in turn may be used to control digital amplifiers and filters.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Analogue circuits are typically harder to design, requiring more skill than comparable digital systems to conceptualize.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] An analogue circuit is usually designed by hand because the application is built into the hardware.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Digital hardware, on the other hand, has a great deal of commonality across applications and can be mass-produced in a standardised form.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Hardware design consists largely of repeated identical blocks and the design process can be highly automated.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] This is one of the main reasons that digital systems have become more common than analogue devices.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] However, the application of digital hardware is a function of the software/firmware and creating this is still largely a labour-intensive process.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Since the early 2000s, there were some platforms that were developed which enabled analogue design to be defined using software - which allows faster prototyping.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Furthermore, if a digital electronic device is to interact with the real world, it will always need an analogue interface.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] For example, every digital radio receiver has an analogue preamplifier as the first stage in the receive chain.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Design of analogue circuits has been greatly eased by the advent of software circuit simulators such as SPICE.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] IBM developed their own in-house simulator, ASTAP, in the 1970s which used an unusual (compared to other simulators) sparse matrix method of circuit analysis.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Analogue circuits can be entirely passive, consisting of resistors, capacitors and inductors.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Active circuits also contain active elements such as transistors.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] Traditional circuits are built from lumped elements – that is, discrete components.
[src:analog-circuit-design/analogue-electronics] However, an alternative is distributed-element circuits, built from pieces of transmission line.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] A **bandgap voltage reference** is a voltage reference circuit widely used in integrated circuits.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] David Hilbiber of Fairchild Semiconductor filed a patent in 1963 and published this circuit concept in 1964.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Bob Widlar, Paul Brokaw and others followed up with other commercially-successful versions.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] The voltage difference between two p–n junctions (e.g. diodes), operated at different current densities, is used to generate a current that is *proportional to absolute temperature* (*PTAT*) in a resistor.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] This current is used to generate a voltage in a second resistor.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] This voltage in turn is added to the voltage of one of the junctions (or a third one, in some implementations).
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] The voltage across a diode operated at constant current is *complementary to absolute temperature* (*CTAT*), with a temperature coefficient of approximately −2 mV/K.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] If the ratio between the first and second resistor is chosen properly, the first order effects of the temperature dependency of the diode and the PTAT current will cancel out.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] This temperature dependency has a typical parabolic residual behavior since the linear (first order) effects are chosen to cancel.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Because the output voltage is by definition fixed around 1.25 V for typical Si bandgap reference circuits, the minimum operating voltage is about 1.4 V, as in a CMOS circuit at least one drain-source voltage of a field-effect transistor (FET) has to be added.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Therefore, recent work concentrates on finding alternative solutions, in which for example currents are summed instead of voltages, resulting in a lower theoretical limit for the operating voltage.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] The first letter of the acronym, CTAT, is sometimes misconstrued to represent *constant* rather than *complementary*.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] The term, *constant with temperature* (*CWT*), exists to address this confusion, but is not in widespread use.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] When summing a PTAT and a CTAT current, only the linear terms of current are compensated, while the higher-order terms are limiting the temperature drift (TD) of the bandgap reference at around 20 ppm/°C, over a temperature range of 100 °C.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] For this reason, in 2001, Malcovati designed a circuit topology that can compensate high-order non-linearities, thus achieving an improved TD.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] This design used an improved version of Banba's topology and an analysis of base-emitter temperature effects that was performed by Tsividis in 1980.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] In 2012, Andreou has further improved the high-order non-linear compensation by using a second operational amplifier along with an additional resistor leg at the point where the two currents are summed up.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] This method enhanced further the curvature correction and achieved superior TD performance over a wider temperature range.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] In addition it achieved improved line regulation and lower noise.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] The other critical issue in design of bandgap references is power efficiency and size of circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] As a bandgap reference is generally based on BJT devices and resistors, the total size of circuit could be large and therefore expensive for IC design.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Moreover, this type of circuit might consume a lot of power to reach to the desired noise and precision specification.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Despite these limitations, the band gap voltage reference is widely used in voltage regulators, covering the majority of 78xx, 79xx devices along with the TL431 and the complementary LM317 and LM337.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Temperature coefficients as low as 1.5–2.0 ppm/°C can be obtained with bandgap references.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] However, the parabolic characteristic of voltage versus temperature means that a single figure in ppm/°C does not adequately describe the behavior of the circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Manufacturers' data sheets show that the temperature at which the peak (or trough) of the voltage curve occurs is subject to normal sample variations in production.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Bandgap references are also suited for low-power applications.
[src:analog-circuit-design/bandgap-voltage-reference] Mixed-signal microcontrollers may provide an internal bandgap reference signal to be used as reference for any internal comparator(s) and analog-to-digital converter(s).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] A **current mirror** is a circuit designed to copy a current through one active device by controlling the current in another active device of a circuit, keeping the output current constant regardless of loading.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The current being "copied" can be, and sometimes is, a varying signal current.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Conceptually, an ideal current mirror is simply an ideal *inverting current amplifier* that reverses the current direction as well, or it could consist of a current-controlled current source (CCCS).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The current mirror is used to provide bias currents and active loads to circuits.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] It can also be used to model a more realistic current source (since ideal current sources do not exist).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The circuit topology covered here is one that appears in many monolithic integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] It is a Widlar mirror without an emitter degeneration resistor in the follower (output) transistor.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] This topology can only be done in an IC, as the matching has to be extremely close and cannot be achieved with discretes.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Another topology is the Wilson current mirror.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The Wilson mirror solves the Early effect voltage problem in this design.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Current mirrors are applied in both analog and mixed VLSI circuits.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] There are three main specifications that characterize a current mirror.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The first is the transfer ratio (in the case of a current amplifier) or the output current magnitude (in the case of a constant current source CCS).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The second is its AC output resistance, which determines how much the output current varies with the voltage applied to the mirror.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The third specification is the minimum voltage drop across the output part of the mirror necessary to make it work properly.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] This minimum voltage is dictated by the need to keep the output transistor of the mirror in active mode.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The range of voltages where the mirror works is called the **compliance range** and the voltage marking the boundary between good and bad behavior is called the **compliance voltage**.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] There are also a number of secondary performance issues with mirrors, for example, temperature stability.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] For small-signal analysis the current mirror can be approximated by its equivalent Norton impedance.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] In large-signal hand analysis, a current mirror is usually and simply approximated by an ideal current source.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] A bipolar transistor can be used as the simplest *current-to-current converter* but its transfer ratio would highly depend on temperature variations, *β* tolerances, etc.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] To eliminate these undesired disturbances, a current mirror is composed of two cascaded *current-to-voltage* and *voltage-to-current* converters placed at the same conditions and having reverse characteristics.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] It is not obligatory for them to be linear; the only requirement is their characteristics to be mirrorlike (for example, in the BJT current mirror below, they are logarithmic and exponential).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Usually, two identical converters are used but the characteristic of the first one is reversed by applying a negative feedback.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Thus a current mirror consists of two cascaded equal converters (the first – reversed and the second – direct).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] If a voltage is applied to the BJT base-emitter junction as an input quantity and the collector current is taken as an output quantity, the transistor will act as an *exponential voltage-to-current converter*.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] By applying a negative feedback (simply joining the base and collector) the transistor can be "reversed" and it will begin acting as the opposite *logarithmic current-to-voltage converter*; now it will adjust the "output" base-emitter voltage so as to pass the applied "input" collector current.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The simplest bipolar current mirror (shown in Figure 1) implements this idea.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] It consists of two cascaded transistor stages acting accordingly as a *reversed* and *direct* voltage-to-current converters.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The emitter of transistor Q1 is connected to ground.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Its collector and base are tied together, so its collector-base voltage is zero.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Consequently, the voltage drop across Q1 is *V*BE, that is, this voltage is set by the diode law and Q1 is said to be diode connected.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] (See also Ebers-Moll model.) It is important to have Q1 in the circuit instead of a simple diode, because Q1 sets *V*BE for transistor Q2.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] If Q1 and Q2 are matched, that is, have substantially the same device properties, and if the mirror output voltage is chosen so the collector-base voltage of Q2 is also zero, then the *V*BE-value set by Q1 results in an emitter current in the matched Q2 that is the same as the emitter current in Q1.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Because Q1 and Q2 are matched, their *β*0-values also agree, making the mirror output current the same as the collector current of Q1.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] where *IS* is the reverse saturation current or scale current; *V*T, the thermal voltage; and *V*A, the Early voltage.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The reference current supplies the collector current to Q1 and the base currents to both transistors – when both transistors have zero base-collector bias, the two base currents are equal, IB1 = IB2 = IB.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Parameter *β*0 is the transistor *β*-value for *V*CB = 0 V.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] If *V*BC is greater than zero in output transistor Q2, the collector current in Q2 will be somewhat larger than for Q1 due to the Early effect.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] where *V*A is the Early voltage; and *V*CE, the collector-to-emitter voltage of output transistor.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] To keep the output transistor active, *V*CB ≥ 0 V.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] where *V*T is the thermal voltage; and *I*S, the reverse saturation current or scale current.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] When Q2 has *V*CB > 0 V, the transistors no longer are matched.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] where *V*A is the Early voltage and *β*0 is the transistor *β* for *V*CB = 0 V.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Besides the difference due to the Early effect, the transistor *β*-values will differ because the *β*0-values depend on current, and the two transistors now carry different currents (see *Gummel–Poon model*).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Further, Q2 may get substantially hotter than Q1 due to the associated higher power dissipation.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] To maintain matching, the temperature of the transistors must be nearly the same.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] In integrated circuits and transistor arrays where both transistors are on the same die, this is easy to achieve.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] But if the two transistors are widely separated, the precision of the current mirror is compromised.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Additional matched transistors can be connected to the same base and will supply the same collector current.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] In other words, the right half of the circuit can be duplicated several times.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Note, however, that each additional right-half transistor "steals" a bit of collector current from Q1 due to the non-zero base currents of the right-half transistors.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] This will result in a small reduction in the programmed current.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] See also an example of a mirror with emitter degeneration to increase mirror resistance.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] For the simple mirror shown in the diagram, typical values of $\beta$ will yield a current match of 1% or better.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The basic current mirror can also be implemented using MOSFET transistors, as shown in Figure 2.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Transistor M1 is operating in the saturation or active mode, and so is M2.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] In this setup, the output current *I*OUT is directly related to *I*REF, as discussed next.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The drain current of a MOSFET *I*D is a function of both the gate-source voltage and the drain-to-gate voltage of the MOSFET given by *I*D = *f*(*V*GS, *V*DG), a relationship derived from the functionality of the MOSFET device.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] In the case of transistor M1 of the mirror, *I*D = *I*REF.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Reference current *I*REF is a known current, and can be provided by a resistor as shown, or by a "threshold-referenced" or "self-biased" current source to ensure that it is constant, independent of voltage supply variations.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Using *V*DG = 0 for transistor M1, the drain current in M1 is *I*D = *f*(*V*GS, *V*DG=0), so we find: *f*(*V*GS, 0) = *I*REF, implicitly determining the value of *V*GS.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The circuit in the diagram forces the same *V*GS to apply to transistor M2.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The drain-to-source voltage can be expressed as *V*DS = *V*DG + *V*GS.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] where *λ* = channel-length modulation parameter and *V*DS is the drain-to-source bias.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] To keep the output transistor resistance high, *V*DG ≥ 0 V.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] For the Shichman–Hodges model, *f*−1 is approximately a square-root function.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] A useful feature of this mirror is the linear dependence of *f* upon device width *W*, a proportionality approximately satisfied even for models more accurate than the Shichman–Hodges model.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Thus, by adjusting the ratio of widths of the two transistors, multiples of the reference current can be generated.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The Shichman–Hodges model is accurate only for rather dated technology, although it often is used simply for convenience even today.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Any quantitative design based upon new technology uses computer models for the devices that account for the changed current-voltage characteristics.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Among the differences that must be accounted for in an accurate design is the failure of the square law in *V*gs for voltage dependence and the very poor modeling of *V*ds drain voltage dependence provided by *λV*ds.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Another failure of the equations that proves very significant is the inaccurate dependence upon the channel length *L*.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] A significant source of *L*-dependence stems from λ, as noted by Gray and Meyer, who also note that *λ* usually must be taken from experimental data.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Due to the wide variation of *V*th even within a particular device number discrete versions are problematic.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Although the variation can be somewhat compensated for by using a Source degenerate resistor its value becomes so large that the output resistance suffers (i.e. reduces).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] This variation relegates the MOSFET version to the IC/monolithic arena.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Figure 3 shows a mirror using negative feedback to increase output resistance.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Because of the op amp, these circuits are sometimes called **gain-boosted current mirrors**.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Because they have relatively low compliance voltages, they also are called **wide-swing current mirrors**.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] A variety of circuits based upon this idea are in use, particularly for MOSFET mirrors because MOSFETs have rather low intrinsic output resistance values.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] A MOSFET version of Figure 3 is shown in Figure 4, where MOSFETs M3 and M4 operate in ohmic mode to play the same role as emitter resistors *R*E in Figure 3, and MOSFETs M1 and M2 operate in active mode in the same roles as mirror transistors Q1 and Q2 in Figure 3.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] An explanation follows of how the circuit in Figure 3 works.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The operational amplifier is fed the difference in voltages *V*1 − *V*2 at the top of the two emitter-leg resistors of value *R*E.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] This difference is amplified by the op amp and fed to the base of output transistor Q2.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] If the collector base reverse bias on Q2 is increased by increasing the applied voltage *V*A, the current in Q2 increases, increasing *V*2 and decreasing the difference *V*1 − *V*2 entering the op amp.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Consequently, the base voltage of Q2 is decreased, and *V*BE of Q2 decreases, counteracting the increase in output current.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] where *β*1 for transistor Q1 and *β*2 for Q2 differ due to the Early effect if the reverse bias across the collector-base of Q2 is non-zero.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] An idealized treatment of output resistance is given in the footnote.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] A small-signal analysis for an op amp with finite gain *A*v but otherwise ideal is based upon Figure 5 (*β*, *r*O and *r*π refer to Q2).
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] To arrive at Figure 5, notice that the positive input of the op amp in Figure 3 is at AC ground, so the voltage input to the op amp is simply the AC emitter voltage *V*e applied to its negative input, resulting in a voltage output of −*A*v *V*e.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] a substantial improvement over the basic mirror where *R*out = *r*O.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] The small-signal analysis of the MOSFET circuit of Figure 4 is obtained from the bipolar analysis by setting *β* = *g*m *r*π in the formula for *R*out and then letting *r*π → ∞.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] This time, *R*E is the resistance of the source-leg MOSFETs M3, M4.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] Unlike Figure 3, however, as *A*v is increased (holding *R*E fixed in value), *R*out continues to increase, and does not approach a limiting value at large *A*v.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] For Figure 3, a large op amp gain achieves the maximum *R*out with only a small *R*E.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] A low value for *R*E means *V*2 also is small, allowing a low compliance voltage for this mirror, only a voltage *V*2 larger than the compliance voltage of the simple bipolar mirror.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] For this reason this type of mirror also is called a *wide-swing current mirror*, because it allows the output voltage to swing low compared to other types of mirror that achieve a large *R*out only at the expense of large compliance voltages.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] With the MOSFET circuit of Figure 4, like the circuit in Figure 3, the larger the op amp gain *A*v, the smaller *R*E can be made at a given *R*out, and the lower the compliance voltage of the mirror.
[src:analog-circuit-design/current-mirror] These multi-transistor mirror circuits are used both with bipolar and MOS transistors.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] A **differential amplifier** is a type of electronic amplifier that amplifies the difference between two input voltages but suppresses any voltage common to the two inputs.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Single amplifiers are usually implemented by either adding the appropriate feedback resistors to a standard op-amp, or with a dedicated integrated circuit containing internal feedback resistors.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] It is also a common sub-component of larger integrated circuits handling analog signals.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In practice, however, the gain is not quite equal for the two inputs.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] This means, for instance, that if $V_{\text{in}}^{+}$ and $V_{\text{in}}^{-}$ are equal, the output will not be zero, as it would be in the ideal case.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] where $A_{\text{c}}$ is called the common-mode gain of the amplifier.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] As differential amplifiers are often used to null out noise or bias voltages that appear at both inputs, a low common-mode gain is usually desired.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The common-mode rejection ratio (CMRR), usually defined as the ratio between differential-mode gain and common-mode gain, indicates the ability of the amplifier to accurately cancel voltages that are common to both inputs.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In a perfectly symmetric differential amplifier, $A_{\text{c}}$ is zero, and the CMRR is infinite.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Note that a differential amplifier is a more general form of amplifier than one with a single input; by grounding one input of a differential amplifier, a single-ended amplifier results.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Modern differential amplifiers are usually implemented with a basic two-transistor circuit called a *“long-tailed” pair* or *differential pair*.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] This circuit was originally implemented using a pair of vacuum tubes.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The circuit works the same way for all three-terminal devices with current gain.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The bias points of “long-tail” resistor circuit are largely determined by Ohm's law and less so by active-component characteristics.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The long-tailed pair was developed from earlier knowledge of push–pull circuit techniques and measurement bridges.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] An early circuit which closely resembles a long-tailed pair was published by British neurophysiologist Bryan Matthews in 1934, and it seems likely that this was intended to be a true long-tailed pair but was published with a drawing error.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The earliest definite long-tailed pair circuit appears in a patent submitted by Alan Blumlein in 1936.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] By the end of the 1930s the topology was well established and had been described by various authors, including Frank Offner (1937), Otto Schmitt (1937) and Jan Friedrich Toennies (1938), and it was particularly used for detection and measurement of physiological impulses.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The long-tailed pair was very successfully used in early British computing, most notably the Pilot ACE model and descendants, Maurice Wilkes’ EDSAC, and probably others designed by people who worked with Blumlein or his peers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] One disadvantage is that the output voltage swing (typically ±10–20 V) was imposed upon a high DC voltage (200 V or so), requiring care in signal coupling, usually some form of wide-band DC coupling.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Many computers of this time tried to avoid this problem by using only AC-coupled pulse logic, which made them very large and overly complex (ENIAC: 18,000 tubes for a 20-digit calculator) or unreliable.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] DC-coupled circuitry became the norm after the first generation of vacuum-tube computers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] A differential (long-tailed, emitter-coupled) pair amplifier consists of two amplifying stages with common (emitter, source or cathode) degeneration.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] With two inputs and two outputs, this forms a differential amplifier stage (Figure 2).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The two bases (or grids or gates) are inputs which are differentially amplified (subtracted and multiplied) by the transistor pair; they can be fed with a differential (balanced) input signal, or one input could be grounded to form a phase splitter circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] An amplifier with differential output can drive a floating load or another stage with differential input.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] If the differential output is not desired, then only one output can be used (taken from just one of the collectors (or anodes or drains), disregarding the other output; this configuration is referred to as *single-ended output*.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The gain is half that of the stage with differential output.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] To avoid sacrificing gain, a differential to single-ended converter can be utilized.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] This is often implemented as a current mirror (Figure 3, below).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The emitter-coupled amplifier is compensated for temperature drifts, VBE is cancelled, and the Miller effect and transistor saturation are avoided.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] That is why it is used to form emitter-coupled amplifiers (avoiding Miller effect), phase splitter circuits (obtaining two inverse voltages), ECL gates and switches (avoiding transistor saturation), etc.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] To explain the circuit operation, four particular modes are isolated below although, in practice, some of them act simultaneously and their effects are superimposed.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In contrast with classic amplifying stages that are biased from the side of the base (and so they are highly β-dependent), the differential pair is directly biased from the side of the emitters by sinking/injecting the total quiescent current.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The series negative feedback (the emitter degeneration) makes the transistors act as voltage stabilizers; it forces them to adjust their VBE voltages (base currents) to pass the quiescent current through their collector-emitter junctions.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] So, due to the negative feedback, the quiescent current depends only slightly on the transistor's β.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The biasing base currents needed to evoke the quiescent collector currents usually come from the ground, pass through the input sources and enter the bases.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] So, the sources have to be galvanic (DC) to ensure paths for the biasing current and low resistive enough to not create significant voltage drops across them.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Otherwise, additional DC elements should be connected between the bases and the ground (or the positive power supply).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In common mode (the two input voltages change in the same directions), the two voltage (emitter) followers cooperate with each other working together on the common high-resistive emitter load (the "long tail").
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] They all together increase or decrease the voltage of the common emitter point (figuratively speaking, they together "pull up" or "pull down" it so that it moves).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In addition, the dynamic load "helps" them by changing its instant ohmic resistance in the same direction as the input voltages (it increases when the voltage increases and vice versa.) thus keeping up constant total resistance between the two supply rails.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] There is a full (100%) negative feedback; the two input base voltages and the emitter voltage change simultaneously while the collector currents and the total current do not change.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] As a result, the output collector voltages do not change as well.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The collector resistors can be replaced by a current mirror (the top blue section in Fig.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] 3), whose output part acts as an active load.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Thus the differential collector current signal is converted to a single-ended voltage signal without the intrinsic 50% losses, so the gain is doubled.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] This is achieved by copying the input collector current from the left to the right side, where the magnitudes of the two input signals add.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] For this purpose, the input of the current mirror is connected to the left output, and the output of the current mirror is connected to the right output of the differential amplifier.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The current mirror copies the left collector current and passes it through the right transistor that produces the right collector current.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] At this right output of the differential amplifier, the two signal currents (pos. and neg. current changes) are subtracted.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In this case (differential input signal), they are equal and opposite.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Thus, the difference is twice the individual signal currents (Δ*I* − (−Δ*I*) = 2Δ*I*), and the differential to single-ended conversion is completed without gain losses.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] 4 shows the transmission characteristic of this circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The quiescent current has to be constant to ensure constant collector voltages at common mode.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] This requirement is not so important in the case of a differential output, since although their two collector voltages will vary simultaneously their difference (the output voltage) will not vary.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] But in the case of a single-ended output, it is extremely important to keep a constant current since the output collector voltage will vary.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Thus the higher the resistance of the current source $R_{\text{e}}$ in the original circuit of Fig.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] 2, the lower (better) is the common-mode gain $A_{\text{c}}$ .
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The constant current needed could be produced by connecting an element (resistor) with very high resistance between the shared emitter node and the supply rail (negative for NPN and positive for PNP transistors), but that requires a high supply voltage.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] So in more sophisticated designs, an element with high differential (dynamic) resistance approximating a constant current source/sink (the bottom of Fig.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] It is usually implemented by a current mirror because of its high compliance voltage (small voltage drop across the output transistor).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] It is possible to connect a floating source between the two bases, but it is necessary to ensure paths for the biasing base currents.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In the case of galvanic source, only one resistor has to be connected between one of the bases and the ground.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The biasing current will enter directly this base and indirectly (through the input source) the other one.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] If the source is capacitive, two resistors have to be connected between the two bases and the ground to ensure different paths for the base currents.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The input impedance of the differential pair highly depends on the input mode.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] At common mode, the two parts behave as common-collector stages with high emitter loads; so, the input impedances are extremely high.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] At differential mode, they behave as common-emitter stages with grounded emitters; so, the input impedances are low.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The output impedance of the differential pair is high (especially for the improved differential pair with a current mirror as shown in Figure 3).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The common-mode input voltage can vary between the two supply rails but cannot closely reach them since some voltage drops (minimum 1 volt) have to remain across the output transistors of the two current mirrors.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] An operational amplifier, or op-amp, is a differential amplifier with very high differential-mode gain, very high input impedance, and low output impedance.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] An op-amp differential amplifier can be built with predictable and stable gain by applying *negative* feedback (Figure 5).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Some kinds of differential amplifier usually include several simpler differential amplifiers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] For example, a fully differential amplifier, an instrumentation amplifier, or an isolation amplifier are often built from a combination of several op-amps.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Differential amplifiers are found in many circuits that utilize series negative feedback (op-amp follower, non-inverting amplifier, etc.), where one input is used for the input signal, the other for the feedback signal (usually implemented by operational amplifiers).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] For comparison, the old-fashioned inverting single-ended op-amps from the early 1940s could realize only parallel negative feedback by connecting additional resistor networks (an op-amp inverting amplifier is the most popular example).
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] A common application is for the control of motors or servos, as well as for signal amplification applications.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In discrete electronics, a common arrangement for implementing a differential amplifier is the long-tailed pair, which is also usually found as the differential element in most op-amp integrated circuits.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] A long-tailed pair can be used as an analog multiplier with the differential voltage as one input and the biasing current as another.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] A differential amplifier is used as the input stage emitter coupled logic gates and as switch.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] When used as a switch, the "left" base/grid is used as signal input and the "right" base/grid is grounded; output is taken from the right collector/plate.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] When the input is zero or negative, the output is close to zero (but can be not saturated); when the input is positive, the output is most-positive, dynamic operation being the same as the amplifier use described above.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The differential amplifier is used in the cathode follower oscillator.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] The advantages are high impedance of the differential amplifier input and output and small phase shift between input and output.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] This application uses only one input and one output of the differential amplifier.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In case the operational amplifier's (non-ideal) input bias current or differential input impedance are a significant effect, one can select a feedback network that improves the effect of common-mode input signal and bias.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] In Figure 6, current generators model the input bias current at each terminal; *I*+b and *I*−b represent the input bias current at terminals *V*+ and *V*− respectively.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] which implies that the closed-loop gain for the differential signal is *V*+in − *V*−in, but the common-mode gain is identically zero.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] It also implies that the common-mode input bias current has cancelled out, leaving only the input offset current *I*Δb = *I*+b − *I*−b still present, and with a coefficient of *R*i.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] It is as if the input offset current is equivalent to an input offset voltage acting across an input resistance *R*i, which is the source resistance of the feedback network into the input terminals.
[src:analog-circuit-design/differential-amplifier] Finally, as long as the open-loop voltage gain *A*ol is much larger than unity, the closed-loop voltage gain is *R*f/*R*i, the value one would obtain through the rule-of-thumb analysis known as "virtual ground".
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] An **operational amplifier** (often **op amp**, **op-amp**, or **opamp**) is a DC-coupled electronic amplifier with a differential input, a (usually) single-ended output voltage, and an extremely high gain.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Its name comes from its original use of performing mathematical operations in analog computers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The **voltage-feedback opamp** (**VFOA** or **VFA**, the focus of this article) amplifies the voltage difference between its two inputs, while the less common *current-feedback op amp* (CFOA) amplifies the current between its two inputs.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] By using negative feedback, the characteristics of an op amp application circuit (e.g., its gain, input and output impedance, bandwidth, and functionality) can be determined by external components and have little dependence on temperature coefficients or engineering tolerance in the op amp itself.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] This flexibility has made the op amp a popular building block in analog circuits.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Today, op amps are used widely in consumer, industrial, and scientific electronics.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Many standard integrated circuit op amps cost only a few cents; however, some integrated or hybrid operational amplifiers with special performance specifications may cost over US$100.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Op amps may be packaged as components or used as elements of more complex integrated circuits.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The op amp is one type of differential amplifier.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The amplifier's differential inputs consist of a non-inverting input (+) with voltage *V*+ and an inverting input (−) with voltage *V*−; ideally the op amp amplifies only the difference in voltage between the two, which is called the *differential input voltage*.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The output voltage of the op amp *V*out is given by the equation $V_{\text{out}}=A_{\text{OL}}(V_{+}-V_{-}),$ where *A*OL is the open-loop gain of the amplifier (the term "open-loop" refers to the absence of an external feedback loop from the output to the input).
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The magnitude of *A*OL is typically very large (100,000 or more for integrated circuit op amps, corresponding to +100 dB).
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Thus, even small microvolts of difference between *V*+ and *V*− may drive the amplifier into clipping or saturation.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The magnitude of *A*OL is not well controlled by the manufacturing process, and so it is impractical to use an open-loop amplifier as a stand-alone differential amplifier.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Without negative feedback, and optionally positive feedback for regeneration, an *open-loop* op amp acts as a comparator, although comparator ICs are better suited.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] If the inverting input of an ideal op amp is held at ground (0 V), and the input voltage *V*in applied to the non-inverting input is positive, the output will be maximum positive; if *V*in is negative, the output will be maximum negative.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] If predictable operation is desired, negative feedback is used by applying a portion of the output voltage to the inverting input.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The *closed-loop* feedback greatly reduces the gain of the circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] When negative feedback is used, the circuit's overall gain and response are determined primarily by the feedback network, rather than by the op-amp characteristics.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] If the feedback network is made of components with values small relative to the op amp's input impedance, the value of the op amp's open-loop response *A*OL does not seriously affect the circuit's performance.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] In this context, high input impedance at the input terminals and low output impedance at the output terminal(s) are particularly useful features of an op amp.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The response of the op-amp circuit with its input, output, and feedback circuits to an input is characterized mathematically by a transfer function; designing an op-amp circuit to have a desired transfer function is in the realm of electrical engineering.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The transfer functions are important in most applications of op amps, such as in analog computers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] In the non-inverting amplifier on the right, the presence of negative feedback via the voltage divider *R*f, *R*g determines the *closed-loop gain* *A*CL = *V*out / *V*in.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Equilibrium will be established when *V*out is just sufficient to pull the inverting input to the same voltage as *V*in.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The voltage gain of the entire circuit is thus 1 + *R*f / *R*g.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] As a simple example, if *V*in = 1 V and Rf = *R*g, *V*out will be 2 V, exactly the amount required to keep *V*− at 1 V.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Because of the feedback provided by the *R*f, *R*g network, this is a *closed-loop* circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The input impedance of the (+) and (−) pins is much larger than other resistances in the circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The first rule only applies in the usual case where the op amp is used in a negative feedback design, where there is a signal path of some sort feeding back from the output to the inverting input.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] These rules are commonly used as a good first approximation for analyzing or designing op-amp circuits.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] None of these ideals can be perfectly realized.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] A real op amp may be modeled with non-infinite or non-zero parameters using equivalent resistors and capacitors in the op-amp model.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The designer can then include these effects in the overall performance of the final circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Some parameters may turn out to have negligible effect on the final design, while others represent actual limitations of the final performance.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Real op amps differ from the ideal model in various aspects.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] is finite in real operational amplifiers.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Typical devices exhibit open-loop DC gain exceeding 100,000.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] (i.e., the product of open-loop and feedback gains) is very large, the closed-loop gain will be determined entirely by the amount of negative feedback (i.e., it will be independent of open-loop gain).
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] In applications where the closed-loop gain must be very high (approaching the open-loop gain), the feedback gain will be very low and the lower loop gain in these cases causes non-ideal behavior from the circuit.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Low output impedance is important for low-impedance loads; for these loads, the voltage drop across the output impedance effectively reduces the open-loop gain.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] In configurations with a voltage-sensing negative feedback, the output impedance of the amplifier is effectively lowered; thus, in linear applications, op-amp circuits usually exhibit a very low output impedance.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] in the output stage and will dissipate more power, so low-power designs may purposely sacrifice low output impedance.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] is the impedance from each input to ground.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] can be a critical issue for high-frequency operation, where it reduces input impedance and may cause phase shifts.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] When high resistances or sources with high output impedances are used in the circuit, these small currents can produce significant voltage drops.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] inputs are matched, then those voltages at each input will be equal.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] between its inputs, these matched voltages will have no effect.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] It is more common for the input currents to be slightly mismatched.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] This offset voltage can create offsets or drift in the operational amplifier.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Input offset voltage is a voltage required across the op amp's input terminals to drive the output voltage to zero.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] In the perfect amplifier, there would be no input offset voltage.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] However, it exists because of imperfections in the differential amplifier input stage of op amps.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Input offset voltage creates two problems: First, due to the amplifier's high voltage gain, it virtually assures that the amplifier output will go into saturation if it is operated without negative feedback, even when the input terminals are wired together.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Second, in a closed-loop, negative-feedback configuration, the input offset voltage is amplified along with the signal and this may pose a problem if high precision DC amplification is required or if the input signal is very small.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] A perfect operational amplifier amplifies only the voltage difference between its two inputs, completely rejecting all voltages that are common to both.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] However, the differential input stage of an operational amplifier is never perfect, leading to the amplification of these common voltages to some degree.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] The output of a perfect operational amplifier will be independent of power supply voltage fluctuations.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] (PSRR) that reflects how well the op amp can reject noise in its power supply from propagating to the output.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] With increasing frequency, the power-supply rejection usually gets worse.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Performance and properties of the amplifier typically change, to some extent, with changes in temperature.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Temperature drift of the input offset voltage is especially important.
[src:analog-circuit-design/operational-amplifier] Real op-amp parameters are subject to slow change over time and with changes in temperature, input conditions, etc.
